📘 Configuring a Simple Router-to-PC Network in Packet Tracer
🔹 Objective

Connect two PCs through a router, assign IP addresses, and enable communication (ping) between them.

🔹 Topology

Router ISR4331 with two interfaces:

Gig0/0/0 → PC1

Gig0/0/1 → PC0

PC0 connected directly to router

PC1 connected directly to router

🔹 IP Addressing Plan
Device	Interface	IP Address	Subnet Mask	Default Gateway
Router	Gig0/0/0	192.168.1.1	255.255.255.0	–
Router	Gig0/0/1	192.168.0.1	255.255.255.0	–
PC0	Fa0	192.168.0.2	255.255.255.0	192.168.0.1
PC1	Fa0	192.168.1.2	255.255.255.0	192.168.1.1
🔹 Router Configuration

On the router CLI:

Router> enable
Router# configure terminal

! Interface to PC1
Router(config)# interface gig0/0/0
Router(config-if)# ip address 192.168.1.1 255.255.255.0
Router(config-if)# no shutdown
Router(config-if)# exit

! Interface to PC0
Router(config)# interface gig0/0/1
Router(config-if)# ip address 192.168.0.1 255.255.255.0
Router(config-if)# no shutdown
Router(config-if)# exit

Router(config)# end
Router# write memory

🔹 PC Configuration

Go to Desktop → IP Configuration:

PC0: IP 192.168.0.2, Mask 255.255.255.0, Gateway 192.168.0.1

PC1: IP 192.168.1.2, Mask 255.255.255.0, Gateway 192.168.1.1

🔹 Verification

On Router:

show ip interface brief


(Interfaces should show “up” with correct IPs).

On PCs:
Open Command Prompt →

ping 192.168.0.1   (PC0 → Router)
ping 192.168.1.1   (PC1 → Router)
ping 192.168.1.2   (PC0 → PC1 through router)
